<div style="background-color:#020D24; color: white; margin:1em; padding:5px 5px; border:4px solid #01091a; border-radius: 4px"><span style="text-shadow: 0 0 10px #C6D7FF"></span>{{Class 5|safety=Severely Dangerous|security=Physical and Psychological Hazards|entity=Presence of One Lethal Entity}}


<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Level 0.66''', often referred to as "The Cold Lobby," is a sub-level between [[Level 0]] and [[Level 1]].</span>

==<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Description'''</span>==
{{Blurimage|file=0_66.jpg|hovertext=Why is it so cold?|caption=The only known image of '''Level 0.66'''. Photographer's whereabouts are unknown.}}
{{Blurimage|file=rendition.jpg|hovertext=M.C. Escher, is that you?|caption=An artistic rendition of what Level 0.66 may look like to a wanderer.}}

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Although '''Level 0.66''' shares a virtually identical layout to [[Level 0]], there are key differences between the two. Firstly, '''Level 0.66''' has inconsistent geometry, with walls shifting and reorienting themselves haphazardly. It is currently unknown what causes the walls to move, but because of this, simply attempting to traverse this level is incredibly dangerous. Due to the nature of the laser measuring instruments normally used to ascertain dimensions, along with the unstable behavior of the walls, it is unfeasable to map out or measure this level.

<span style="font-family:Arno;">The level is incredibly cold, with temperatures averaging approximately -128.2°F (-89°C) throughout the entire level. This makes the level almost uninhabitable, unless you are sufficiently equipped to handle the harsh temperatures of '''Level 0.66''', and causes a myriad of conditions, which include but are not limited to chilblains, frostbite, and hypothermia. 

<span style="font-family:Arno;">The level's visuals are particularly striking. '''Level 0.66''' is tinted in a deep blue that engulfs the entire level, caused by unidentified particulates in the air which scatter longer wavelengths of light. This is with the exception of the Twilight Zone, which is detailed below. 

<span style="font-family:Arno;">What is most interesting about the air in '''Level 0.66''' is that prolonged inhalation causes wanderers to not only lose their sanity, but exposure results in a progressive failure of linear spacial processing. Wanderers begin to lose Cartesian interpretation of their surroundings, with visual input being internally reconstructed in a radial or angular reference frame. As a result, wanderers become unable to keep themselves upright and maneuver through the level, as their perception of the level is that of curved corridors, circular drift in geometry, and the loss of horizontal alignment. The consequences of both the inhalation of the level's air and the brain's deterioration in visual processing are disorientation, nausea, vomiting, headaches, and in extreme cases asphyxiation, brain hemorrhage, and death.

<span style="font-family:Arno;">The use of respirators and gas masks inhibits the air's effect on a wanderer's vision, and the consumption of almond water restores correct visual processing and relieves the wanderer of their symptoms. Survivors of '''Level 0.66''' have stated that the deterioration of their sight bares a resemblance to M.C. Escher's works, but where Escher's work preserved locally correct perspective rules, this level does not.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Curiously, '''Level 0.66''' exhibits a persistent negative electrostatic bias across its atmosphere and structural material. Foreign bodies and living creatures maintain a relatively stable electrochemical equilibrium compared to the surrounding environment, '''creating measurable local field discontinuities''', and inducing chronic electromagnetic instability in conventional electronic systems. Devices exposed to the environment exhibit increasing signal entropy, resulting in progressive data corruption, sensor drift, and intermittent discharge events.</span>

===<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''The Active Period'''</span>===
<span style="font-family:Arno;">As implied, this is the period of time in which the walls of '''Level 0.66''' are jutting around the level and moving haphazardly at deadly speeds. From observation, it is apparent that a wall can spin about three-quarters of a full revolution with two degrees of rotational freedom. The walls of the level cover large distances in extremely short periods of time, often shifting by up to a foot in the time it takes a human to blink, while phasing through other walls and the ceiling.</span>

===<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''The Stationary Period'''</span>===
<span style="font-family:Arno;">The Stationary Period is a period of time, lasting anywhere from 5 to 20 seconds, where every wall in the level stops shifting. A Stationary Period may occur randomly in a 4 to 48 hour interval. If a wall was previously mid-motion and was clipping into another wall, the floor, or the ceiling, the wall will simply move to an unclipped, stable position, before snapping back to its position and rotation once the Period is over.</span>

===<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''The Twilight Zone'''</span>===
<span style="font-family:Arno;">The Twilight Zone is a distinct region of '''Level 0.66'''. Instances of the Twilight Zone can appear anywhere within the level and may span several hundred miles in area. The Zone possesses the property of nullifying all light sources to wanderers once within its boundaries, rendering sight impossible. Despite this, the Zone is completely indistinguishable from the surrounding environment to any observer not in its limits.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">The Zone can be observed from outside it safely, as the nullification effect does not take effect unless the wanderer is inside it. Any light source introduced into the Zone becomes fully suppressed and cannot illuminate whatsoever, making internal navigation completely dependent on external positioning and pre-established reference points.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">It is strongly recommended that wanderers immediately retreat upon accidental entry, as prolonged exposure to the Twilight Zone has been observed to rapidly degrade sanity. Exploration is further limited by the strength and positioning of external light sources placed along its perimeter. The only perceived benefit to entering the bounds of the Twilight Zone is that, due to the complete inability to see from within it, wanderers may find relief from the level's effects on visual processing.</span>

==<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Entities'''</span>==
<span style="font-family:Arno;">A single entity calls '''Level 0.66''' home, that being the Lurker. This entity is native to '''Level 0.66''' and there have been no confirmed sightings of it within any other level. There is only one instance of the Lurker present in '''Level 0.66'''.</span>

<span class="mw-customtoggle-finalchanging mw-customtoggle-initialchanging"><div class="mw-collapsible" id="mw-customcollapsible-initialchanging">
<span style="color:#968736">'''▸ Open <span style="font-family:Arno;">Lurker</span>'''</span></div></span> <div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-finalchanging"> <div class="mw-customtoggle-finalchanging mw-customtoggle-initialchanging"> <span style="color:#968736">'''▾ Close <span style="font-family:Arno;">Lurker</span>'''</span></div> </div> <div class="mw-collapsible mw-collapsed" id="mw-customcollapsible-finalchanging"> <div style="background-color:#020A1D; color: white; margin:1em; padding:5px 10px; border:2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 3px">
===<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''The Lurker'''</span>===
<span style="font-family:Arno;">In the pitch-black expanse of the Twilight Zone of '''Level 0.66''', the Lurker has resisted all attempts at full visual confirmation except with those it hunts. Sonar imaging reconstructions suggest a large, sexless, facultatively bipedal quadruped measuring approximately 7 feet, 10 inches (~239 centimeters) when upright. The entity is encased in a rigid, chitin-like exoskeleton of uniform smoothness and high apparent structural integrity.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Its postcranial musculature is loosely comparable to that of G. b. beringei (mountain gorilla), though significantly exaggerated in tensile density. The Lurker possesses four primary limbs enabling quadrupedal locomotion, each ending in pentadactyl structures with opposable digits and joint articulation comparable to primate elbows and knees. It moves silently under most recorded conditions, making it difficult to know when it is near.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">The Lurker's head is similar in shape to Varanus komodoensis (Komodo dragon), though lacking any eyes or other structures used for visual processing. Instead, the Lurker appears to operate through a layered sensory system. Primary tracking is believed to rely on the detection of electrostatic field gradients within '''Level 0.66''', where foreign matter induces subtle but persistent distortions in the ambient imbalance of the environment. At mid-range, directional certainty increases as these gradients stabilize, while close-range acquisition appears to involve an additional chemical or organic confirmation process, though the exact mechanism remains unclear. Despite the absence of eyes, the entity demonstrates precise navigation through unstable regions and around the moving walls of the level.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Under normal level conditions, the Lurker remains entirely passive and does not attack any wanderers even when provoked. During the Stationary Periods of '''Level 0.66''', however, it has been seen to hunt. At this time, the entity appears to register non-native presence through electrostatic disruptions, and will initiate pursuit. It moves in a quadrupedal gait, reaching bursts of approximately 120 miles per hour (~193 kilometers per hour), with reported instances of near-instant positional shifts through collapsed or unstable geometry, though the method of traversal remains unconfirmed. Once tracking stabilizes, the Lurker closes distance with increasing precision, culminating in direct interception. Upon reaching its target, it rises to a bipedal stance, securing its target using elongated digits which secrete a fast-acting paralytic agent, capable of inhibiting nerve signals to muscles in as short as two seconds.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Following immobilization, the Lurker begins to feed, characterized by a relaxation of the jaw, revealing a bioluminescent uvula unaffected by the Twilight Zone's light nullification. A low-frequency droning has been recorded during this phase. The entity proceeds to decapitate its prey, eating only the head, before discarding the remaining body. After ingestion, the Lurker returns to a passive state and has been observed to refrain from initiating further hunts for up to six hours after feeding (in most cases).</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Deterrence is possible through interference with the Lurker's olfactory system. Strong, pungent organic odors cause the entity severe discomfort, particularly compounds associated with Allium species, including onions, garlic, and shallots (Amaryllidaceae). In the absence of such materials, flatulence has demonstrated a "semi-effective" method of deterrence, though application conditions are inconsistent and situationally dependent.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">It must be made clear that the Lurker will not allow itself to be directly observed. If its feeding cycle causes it to leave the confines of a Twilight Zone, <u>'''it will proceed to kill anyone who has observed it'''</u>. Extreme caution is advised, and if a member of your party has been chosen for feeding by the Lurker, your only choice is to avoid making visual contact with it at all costs.</span>
</div>

</div><br>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">There have been zero confirmed cases of any other entities in this level.</span>

==<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Colonies and Outposts'''</span>==
<span style="font-family:Arno;">This level is devoid of formal colonies and outposts, with the only other wanderers present being individuals who have become stranded within it. There are several reasons for this, as follows:</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">- The method of entry is complex and tedious, rendering the establishment of any permanent human settlement within this level impractical.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">- '''Level 0.66''' contains no utilizable resources for wanderers, and nothing can be cultivated due to the level's extreme temperatures.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">- The environmental conditions make sustained habitation nearly impossible for prolonged periods.</span>

==<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Entrances and Exits'''</span>==

===<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Entrances'''</span>===
<span style="font-family:Arno;">To guarantee entry into '''Level 0.66''', you must follow very specific instructions, which are as follows:
#<span style="font-family:Arno;">Find a vent within [[Level 0]]. Enter, and begin crawling through it.
#<span style="font-family:Arno;">After crawling for anywhere from 1 to 17 miles, the vent will experience a temperature drop. This drop will be noticeable no matter what protective gear you wear.
#<span style="font-family:Arno;">Once the temperature drop occurs, begin crawling in the opposite direction for half a mile.
#<span style="font-family:Arno;">After you have crawled half a mile in reverse, you will fall through the floor of the vent and end up in a room with two doors labelled '''COLD''' and '''HOT'''
#<span style="font-family:Arno;">You must go through the door labelled '''COLD'''. Once you do, you will be sent to a random location within '''Level 0.66'''.
<span style="font-family:Arno;">Failure to complete any of these steps correctly will send you to an unknown location. No wanderer that failed to complete these steps was ever heard from again, therefore it is advised to be as careful as possible if you plan to go to this level.

<span style="font-family:Arno;">Unknown factors in [[Level 483.3]] may lead here, and the "karma coasters" in [[Level 995]] have been speculated to send you here if your karma is between -100 and -150.</span>

<span style="font-family:Arno;">As there have been no other documented or confirmed methods of entry into the level, you should not attempt any alternative entry methods.</span>

===<span style="font-family:Arno;">'''Exits'''</span>===
<span style="font-family:Arno;">To exit '''Level 0.66''', you can attempt to no-clip through a wall during the stationary period of the level. Successfully no-clipping in this scenario will send you to a random level between [[Level 2]] and [[Level 41]]. There have been unconfirmed reports of people exiting '''Level 0.66''' and ending up in [[the Hub]], but the validity of these claims is not known.
</span>

